#, no-wrap
msgid "MOUNT OPTIONS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"This section describes mount options specific to BTRFS\\&. For the generic "
"mount options please refer to B<mount>(8) manpage\\&. The options are sorted "
"alphabetically (discarding the I<no> prefix)\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<Note>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"most mount options apply to the whole filesystem and only options in the "
"first mounted subvolume will take effect\\&. This is due to lack of "
"implementation and may change in the future\\&. This means that (for "
"example) you can\\(cqt set per-subvolume I<nodatacow>, I<nodatasum>, or "
"I<compress> using mount options\\&. This should eventually be fixed, but it "
"has proved to be difficult to implement correctly within the Linux VFS "
"framework\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"Mount options are processed in order, only the last occurrence of an option "
"takes effect and may disable other options due to constraints (see eg\\&. "
"I<nodatacow> and I<compress>)\\&. The output of I<mount> command shows which "
"options have been applied\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<acl>, B<noacl>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(default: on)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable/disable support for Posix Access Control Lists (ACLs)\\&. See the "
"B<acl>(5) manual page for more information about ACLs\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The support for ACL is build-time configurable (BTRFS_FS_POSIX_ACL) and "
"mount fails if I<acl> is requested but the feature is not compiled in\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<autodefrag>, B<noautodefrag>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.0, default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable automatic file defragmentation\\&. When enabled, small random writes "
"into files (in a range of tens of kilobytes, currently it\\(cqs 64K) are "
"detected and queued up for the defragmentation process\\&. Not well suited "
"for large database workloads\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The read latency may increase due to reading the adjacent blocks that make "
"up the range for defragmentation, successive write will merge the blocks in "
"the new location\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<Warning>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Defragmenting with Linux kernel versions E<lt> 3\\&.9 or \\(E<gt>= 3\\&.14-"
"rc2 as well as with Linux stable kernel versions \\(E<gt>= 3\\&.10\\&.31, "
"\\(E<gt>= 3\\&.12\\&.12 or \\(E<gt>= 3\\&.13\\&.4 will break up the reflinks "
"of COW data (for example files copied with B<cp --reflink>, snapshots or de-"
"duplicated data)\\&. This may cause considerable increase of space usage "
"depending on the broken up reflinks\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<barrier>, B<nobarrier>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Ensure that all IO write operations make it through the device cache and are "
"stored permanently when the filesystem is at its consistency checkpoint\\&. "
"This typically means that a flush command is sent to the device that will "
"synchronize all pending data and ordinary metadata blocks, then writes the "
"superblock and issues another flush\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The write flushes incur a slight hit and also prevent the IO block scheduler "
"to reorder requests in a more effective way\\&. Disabling barriers gets rid "
"of that penalty but will most certainly lead to a corrupted filesystem in "
"case of a crash or power loss\\&. The ordinary metadata blocks could be yet "
"unwritten at the time the new superblock is stored permanently, expecting "
"that the block pointers to metadata were stored permanently before\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"On a device with a volatile battery-backed write-back cache, the "
"I<nobarrier> option will not lead to filesystem corruption as the pending "
"blocks are supposed to make it to the permanent storage\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<check_int>, B<check_int_data>, B<check_int_print_mask=>I<value>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"These debugging options control the behavior of the integrity checking "
"module (the BTRFS_FS_CHECK_INTEGRITY config option required)\\&. The main "
"goal is to verify that all blocks from a given transaction period are "
"properly linked\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"I<check_int> enables the integrity checker module, which examines all block "
"write requests to ensure on-disk consistency, at a large memory and CPU cost"
"\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"I<check_int_data> includes extent data in the integrity checks, and implies "
"the I<check_int> option\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"I<check_int_print_mask> takes a bitmask of BTRFSIC_PRINT_MASK_* values as "
"defined in I<fs/btrfs/check-integrity\\&.c>, to control the integrity "
"checker module behavior\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"See comments at the top of I<fs/btrfs/check-integrity\\&.c> for more "
"information\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<clear_cache>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Force clearing and rebuilding of the disk space cache if something has gone "
"wrong\\&. See also: I<space_cache>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<commit=>I<seconds>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.12, default: 30)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Set the interval of periodic transaction commit when data are synchronized "
"to permanent storage\\&. Higher interval values lead to larger amount of "
"unwritten data, which has obvious consequences when the system crashes\\&. "
"The upper bound is not forced, but a warning is printed if it\\(cqs more "
"than 300 seconds (5 minutes)\\&. Use with care\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"B<compress>, B<compress=>I<type[:level]>, B<compress-force>, B<compress-"
"force=>I<type[:level]>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "(default: off, level support since: 5\\&.1)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Control BTRFS file data compression\\&. Type may be specified as I<zlib>, "
"I<lzo>, I<zstd> or I<no> (for no compression, used for remounting)\\&. If no "
"type is specified, I<zlib> is used\\&. If I<compress-force> is specified, "
"then compression will always be attempted, but the data may end up "
"uncompressed if the compression would make them larger\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"Both I<zlib> and I<zstd> (since version 5\\&.1) expose the compression level "
"as a tunable knob with higher levels trading speed and memory (I<zstd>) for "
"higher compression ratios\\&. This can be set by appending a colon and the "
"desired level\\&. Zlib accepts the range [1, 9] and zstd accepts [1, 15]\\&. "
"If no level is set, both currently use a default level of 3\\&. The value 0 "
"is an alias for the default level\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Otherwise some simple heuristics are applied to detect an incompressible file"
"\\&. If the first blocks written to a file are not compressible, the whole "
"file is permanently marked to skip compression\\&. As this is too simple, "
"the I<compress-force> is a workaround that will compress most of the files "
"at the cost of some wasted CPU cycles on failed attempts\\&. Since kernel "
"4\\&.15, a set of heuristic algorithms have been improved by using frequency "
"sampling, repeated pattern detection and Shannon entropy calculation to "
"avoid that\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"If compression is enabled, I<nodatacow> and I<nodatasum> are disabled\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<datacow>, B<nodatacow>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable data copy-on-write for newly created files\\&.  I<Nodatacow> implies "
"I<nodatasum>, and disables I<compression>\\&. All files created under "
"I<nodatacow> are also set the NOCOW file attribute (see B<chattr>(1))\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"If I<nodatacow> or I<nodatasum> are enabled, compression is disabled\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Updates in-place improve performance for workloads that do frequent "
"overwrites, at the cost of potential partial writes, in case the write is "
"interrupted (system crash, device failure)\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<datasum>, B<nodatasum>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable data checksumming for newly created files\\&.  I<Datasum> implies "
"I<datacow>, ie\\&. the normal mode of operation\\&. All files created under "
"I<nodatasum> inherit the \"no checksums\" property, however there\\(cqs no "
"corresponding file attribute (see B<chattr>(1))\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"There is a slight performance gain when checksums are turned off, the "
"corresponding metadata blocks holding the checksums do not need to updated"
"\\&. The cost of checksumming of the blocks in memory is much lower than the "
"IO, modern CPUs feature hardware support of the checksumming algorithm\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<degraded>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Allow mounts with less devices than the RAID profile constraints require\\&. "
"A read-write mount (or remount) may fail when there are too many devices "
"missing, for example if a stripe member is completely missing from RAID0\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Since 4\\&.14, the constraint checks have been improved and are verified on "
"the chunk level, not an the device level\\&. This allows degraded mounts of "
"filesystems with mixed RAID profiles for data and metadata, even if the "
"device number constraints would not be satisfied for some of the profiles\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Example: metadata \\(em raid1, data \\(em single, devices \\(em /dev/sda, /"
"dev/sdb"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Suppose the data are completely stored on I<sda>, then missing I<sdb> will "
"not prevent the mount, even if 1 missing device would normally prevent "
"(any)  I<single> profile to mount\\&. In case some of the data chunks are "
"stored on I<sdb>, then the constraint of single/data is not satisfied and "
"the filesystem cannot be mounted\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<device=>I<devicepath>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Specify a path to a device that will be scanned for BTRFS filesystem during "
"mount\\&. This is usually done automatically by a device manager (like udev) "
"or using the B<btrfs device scan> command (eg\\&. run from the initial "
"ramdisk)\\&. In cases where this is not possible the I<device> mount option "
"can help\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"booting eg\\&. a RAID1 system may fail even if all filesystem\\(cqs "
"I<device> paths are provided as the actual device nodes may not be "
"discovered by the system at that point\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<discard>, B<discard=sync>, B<discard=async>, B<nodiscard>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "(default: off, async support since: 5\\&.6)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"Enable discarding of freed file blocks\\&. This is useful for SSD devices, "
"thinly provisioned LUNs, or virtual machine images; however, every storage "
"layer must support discard for it to work\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"In the synchronous mode (I<sync> or without option value), lack of "
"asynchronous queued TRIM on the backing device TRIM can severely degrade "
"performance, because a synchronous TRIM operation will be attempted instead"
"\\&. Queued TRIM requires newer than SATA revision 3\\&.1 chipsets and "
"devices\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"The asynchronous mode (I<async>) gathers extents in larger chunks before "
"sending them to the devices for TRIM\\&. The overhead and performance impact "
"should be negligible compared to the previous mode and it\\(cqs supposed to "
"be the preferred mode if needed\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"If it is not necessary to immediately discard freed blocks, then the "
"B<fstrim> tool can be used to discard all free blocks in a batch\\&. "
"Scheduling a TRIM during a period of low system activity will prevent latent "
"interference with the performance of other operations\\&. Also, a device may "
"ignore the TRIM command if the range is too small, so running a batch "
"discard has a greater probability of actually discarding the blocks\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<enospc_debug>, B<noenospc_debug>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable verbose output for some ENOSPC conditions\\&. It\\(cqs safe to use "
"but can be noisy if the system reaches near-full state\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<fatal_errors=>I<action>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.4, default: bug)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "Action to take when encountering a fatal error\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<bug>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"I<BUG()> on a fatal error, the system will stay in the crashed state and may "
"be still partially usable, but reboot is required for full operation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<panic>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"I<panic()> on a fatal error, depending on other system configuration, this "
"may be followed by a reboot\\&. Please refer to the documentation of kernel "
"boot parameters, eg\\&.  I<panic>, I<oops> or I<crashkernel>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<flushoncommit>, B<noflushoncommit>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"This option forces any data dirtied by a write in a prior transaction to "
"commit as part of the current commit, effectively a full filesystem sync\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"This makes the committed state a fully consistent view of the file system "
"from the application\\(cqs perspective (i\\&.e\\&. it includes all completed "
"file system operations)\\&. This was previously the behavior only when a "
"snapshot was created\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"When off, the filesystem is consistent but buffered writes may last more "
"than one transaction commit\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<fragment=>I<type>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"(depends on compile-time option BTRFS_DEBUG, since: 4\\&.4, default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"A debugging helper to intentionally fragment given I<type> of block groups"
"\\&. The type can be I<data>, I<metadata> or I<all>\\&. This mount option "
"should not be used outside of debugging environments and is not recognized "
"if the kernel config option I<BTRFS_DEBUG> is not enabled\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<inode_cache>, B<noinode_cache>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"Enable free inode number caching\\&. Not recommended to use unless files on "
"your filesystem get assigned inode numbers that are approaching 264\\&. "
"Normally, new files in each subvolume get assigned incrementally (plus one "
"from the last time) and are not reused\\&. The mount option turns on caching "
"of the existing inode numbers and reuse of inode numbers of deleted files\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"This option may slow down your system at first run, or after mounting "
"without the option\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Defaults to off due to a potential overflow problem when the free space "
"checksums don\\(cqt fit inside a single page\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"Don\\(cqt use this option unless you really need it\\&. The inode number "
"limit on 64bit system is 264, which is practically enough for the whole "
"filesystem lifetime\\&. Due to implementation of linux VFS layer, the inode "
"numbers on 32bit systems are only 32 bits wide\\&. This lowers the limit "
"significantly and makes it possible to reach it\\&. In such case, this mount "
"option will help\\&. Alternatively, files with high inode numbers can be "
"copied to a new subvolume which will effectively start the inode numbers "
"from the beginning again\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<nologreplay>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "(default: off, even read-only)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"The tree-log contains pending updates to the filesystem until the full commit"
"\\&. The log is replayed on next mount, this can be disabled by this option"
"\\&. See also I<treelog>\\&. Note that I<nologreplay> is the same as "
"I<norecovery>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"currently, the tree log is replayed even with a read-only mount! To disable "
"that behaviour, mount also with I<nologreplay>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<max_inline=>I<bytes>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(default: min(2048, page size) )"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Specify the maximum amount of space, that can be inlined in a metadata B-"
"tree leaf\\&. The value is specified in bytes, optionally with a K suffix "
"(case insensitive)\\&. In practice, this value is limited by the filesystem "
"block size (named I<sectorsize> at mkfs time), and memory page size of the "
"system\\&. In case of sectorsize limit, there\\(cqs some space unavailable "
"due to leaf headers\\&. For example, a 4k sectorsize, maximum size of inline "
"data is about 3900 bytes\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Inlining can be completely turned off by specifying 0\\&. This will increase "
"data block slack if file sizes are much smaller than block size but will "
"reduce metadata consumption in return\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "the default value has changed to 2048 in kernel 4\\&.6\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<metadata_ratio=>I<value>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(default: 0, internal logic)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Specifies that 1 metadata chunk should be allocated after every I<value> "
"data chunks\\&. Default behaviour depends on internal logic, some percent of "
"unused metadata space is attempted to be maintained but is not always "
"possible if there\\(cqs not enough space left for chunk allocation\\&. The "
"option could be useful to override the internal logic in favor of the "
"metadata allocation if the expected workload is supposed to be metadata "
"intense (snapshots, reflinks, xattrs, inlined files)\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<norecovery>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 4\\&.5, default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Do not attempt any data recovery at mount time\\&. This will disable "
"I<logreplay> and avoids other write operations\\&. Note that this option is "
"the same as I<nologreplay>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The opposite option I<recovery> used to have different meaning but was "
"changed for consistency with other filesystems, where I<norecovery> is used "
"for skipping log replay\\&. BTRFS does the same and in general will try to "
"avoid any write operations\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<rescan_uuid_tree>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.12, default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Force check and rebuild procedure of the UUID tree\\&. This should not "
"normally be needed\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<skip_balance>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.3, default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Skip automatic resume of an interrupted balance operation\\&. The operation "
"can later be resumed with B<btrfs balance resume>, or the paused state can "
"be removed with B<btrfs balance cancel>\\&. The default behaviour is to "
"resume an interrupted balance immediately after a volume is mounted\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<space_cache>, B<space_cache=>I<version>, B<nospace_cache>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"(I<nospace_cache> since: 3\\&.2, I<space_cache=v1> and I<space_cache=v2> "
"since 4\\&.5, default: I<space_cache=v1>)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Options to control the free space cache\\&. The free space cache greatly "
"improves performance when reading block group free space into memory\\&. "
"However, managing the space cache consumes some resources, including a small "
"amount of disk space\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"There are two implementations of the free space cache\\&. The original one, "
"referred to as I<v1>, is the safe default\\&. The I<v1> space cache can be "
"disabled at mount time with I<nospace_cache> without clearing\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"On very large filesystems (many terabytes) and certain workloads, the "
"performance of the I<v1> space cache may degrade drastically\\&. The I<v2> "
"implementation, which adds a new B-tree called the free space tree, "
"addresses this issue\\&. Once enabled, the I<v2> space cache will always be "
"used and cannot be disabled unless it is cleared\\&. Use I<clear_cache,"
"space_cache=v1> or I<clear_cache,nospace_cache> to do so\\&. If I<v2> is "
"enabled, kernels without I<v2> support will only be able to mount the "
"filesystem in read-only mode\\&. The B<btrfs>(8) command currently only has "
"read-only support for I<v2>\\&. A read-write command may be run on a I<v2> "
"filesystem by clearing the cache, running the command, and then remounting "
"with I<space_cache=v2>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"If a version is not explicitly specified, the default implementation will be "
"chosen, which is I<v1>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<ssd>, B<ssd_spread>, B<nossd>, B<nossd_spread>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(default: SSD autodetected)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Options to control SSD allocation schemes\\&. By default, BTRFS will enable "
"or disable SSD optimizations depending on status of a device with respect to "
"rotational or non-rotational type\\&. This is determined by the contents of "
"I</sys/block/DEV/queue/rotational>)\\&. If it is 0, the I<ssd> option is "
"turned on\\&. The option I<nossd> will disable the autodetection\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The optimizations make use of the absence of the seek penalty that\\(cqs "
"inherent for the rotational devices\\&. The blocks can be typically written "
"faster and are not offloaded to separate threads\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Since 4\\&.14, the block layout optimizations have been dropped\\&. This "
"used to help with first generations of SSD devices\\&. Their FTL (flash "
"translation layer) was not effective and the optimization was supposed to "
"improve the wear by better aligning blocks\\&. This is no longer true with "
"modern SSD devices and the optimization had no real benefit\\&. Furthermore "
"it caused increased fragmentation\\&. The layout tuning has been kept intact "
"for the option I<ssd_spread>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The I<ssd_spread> mount option attempts to allocate into bigger and aligned "
"chunks of unused space, and may perform better on low-end SSDs\\&.  "
"I<ssd_spread> implies I<ssd>, enabling all other SSD heuristics as well\\&. "
"The option I<nossd> will disable all SSD options while I<nossd_spread> only "
"disables I<ssd_spread>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<subvol=>I<path>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Mount subvolume from I<path> rather than the toplevel subvolume\\&. The "
"I<path> is always treated as relative to the toplevel subvolume\\&. This "
"mount option overrides the default subvolume set for the given filesystem\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<subvolid=>I<subvolid>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Mount subvolume specified by a I<subvolid> number rather than the toplevel "
"subvolume\\&. You can use B<btrfs subvolume list> of B<btrfs subvolume show> "
"to see subvolume ID numbers\\&. This mount option overrides the default "
"subvolume set for the given filesystem\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"if both I<subvolid> and I<subvol> are specified, they must point at the same "
"subvolume, otherwise the mount will fail\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<thread_pool=>I<number>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(default: min(NRCPUS + 2, 8) )"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The number of worker threads to start\\&. NRCPUS is number of on-line CPUs "
"detected at the time of mount\\&. Small number leads to less parallelism in "
"processing data and metadata, higher numbers could lead to a performance hit "
"due to increased locking contention, process scheduling, cache-line bouncing "
"or costly data transfers between local CPU memories\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<treelog>, B<notreelog>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable the tree logging used for I<fsync> and I<O_SYNC> writes\\&. The tree "
"log stores changes without the need of a full filesystem sync\\&. The log "
"operations are flushed at sync and transaction commit\\&. If the system "
"crashes between two such syncs, the pending tree log operations are replayed "
"during mount\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"currently, the tree log is replayed even with a read-only mount! To disable "
"that behaviour, also mount with I<nologreplay>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The tree log could contain new files/directories, these would not exist on a "
"mounted filesystem if the log is not replayed\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<usebackuproot>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 4\\&.6, default: off)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Enable autorecovery attempts if a bad tree root is found at mount time\\&. "
"Currently this scans a backup list of several previous tree roots and tries "
"to use the first readable\\&. This can be used with read-only mounts as well"
"\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "This option has replaced I<recovery>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<user_subvol_rm_allowed>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Allow subvolumes to be deleted by their respective owner\\&. Otherwise, only "
"the root user can do that\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"historically, any user could create a snapshot even if he was not owner of "
"the source subvolume, the subvolume deletion has been restricted for that "
"reason\\&. The subvolume creation has been restricted but this mount option "
"is still required\\&. This is a usability issue\\&. Since 4\\&.18, the "
"B<rmdir>(2) syscall can delete an empty subvolume just like an ordinary "
"directory\\&. Whether this is possible can be detected at runtime, see "
"I<rmdir_subvol> feature in I<FILESYSTEM FEATURES>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: SS
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
#, no-wrap
msgid "DEPRECATED MOUNT OPTIONS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"List of mount options that have been removed, kept for backward compatibility"
"\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<recovery>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.2, default: off, deprecated since: 4\\&.5)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"this option has been replaced by I<usebackuproot> and should not be used but "
"will work on 4\\&.5+ kernels\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: SS
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
#, no-wrap
msgid "NOTES ON GENERIC MOUNT OPTIONS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Some of the general mount options from B<mount>(8) that affect BTRFS and are "
"worth mentioning\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<noatime>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"under read intensive work-loads, specifying I<noatime> significantly "
"improves performance because no new access time information needs to be "
"written\\&. Without this option, the default is I<relatime>, which only "
"reduces the number of inode atime updates in comparison to the traditional "
"I<strictatime>\\&. The worst case for atime updates under I<relatime> occurs "
"when many files are read whose atime is older than 24 h and which are "
"freshly snapshotted\\&. In that case the atime is updated I<and> COW happens "
"- for each file - in bulk\\&. See also \\m[blue]B<https://lwn\\&.net/"
"Articles/499293/>\\m[] - I<Atime and btrfs: a bad combination? (LWN, "
"2012-05-31)>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Note that I<noatime> may break applications that rely on atime uptimes like "
"the venerable Mutt (unless you use maildir mailboxes)\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
#, no-wrap
msgid "FILESYSTEM FEATURES"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The basic set of filesystem features gets extended over time\\&. The "
"backward compatibility is maintained and the features are optional, need to "
"be explicitly asked for so accidental use will not create incompatibilities"
"\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"There are several classes and the respective tools to manage the features:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "at mkfs time only"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"This is namely for core structures, like the b-tree nodesize or checksum "
"algorithm, see B<mkfs\\&.btrfs>(8) for more details\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "after mkfs, on an unmounted filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Features that may optimize internal structures or add new structures to "
"support new functionality, see B<btrfstune>(8)\\&. The command B<btrfs "
"inspect-internal dump-super device> will dump a superblock, you can map the "
"value of I<incompat_flags> to the features listed below"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "after mkfs, on a mounted filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"The features of a filesystem (with a given UUID) are listed in B</sys/fs/"
"btrfs/UUID/features/>, one file per feature\\&. The status is stored inside "
"the file\\&. The value I<1> is for enabled and active, while I<0> means the "
"feature was enabled at mount time but turned off afterwards\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"Whether a particular feature can be turned on a mounted filesystem can be "
"found in the directory B</sys/fs/btrfs/features/>, one file per feature\\&. "
"The value I<1> means the feature can be enabled\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"List of features (see also B<mkfs\\&.btrfs>(8) section I<FILESYSTEM "
"FEATURES>):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<big_metadata>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.4)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"the filesystem uses I<nodesize> for metadata blocks, this can be bigger than "
"the page size"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<compress_lzo>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 2\\&.6\\&.38)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"the I<lzo> compression has been used on the filesystem, either as a mount "
"option or via B<btrfs filesystem defrag>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<compress_zstd>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 4\\&.14)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"the I<zstd> compression has been used on the filesystem, either as a mount "
"option or via B<btrfs filesystem defrag>\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<default_subvol>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 2\\&.6\\&.34)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "the default subvolume has been set on the filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<extended_iref>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.7)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"increased hardlink limit per file in a directory to 65536, older kernels "
"supported a varying number of hardlinks depending on the sum of all file "
"name sizes that can be stored into one metadata block"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<free_space_tree>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "(since: 4\\&.5)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"free space representation using a dedicated b-tree, successor of v1 space "
"cache"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<metadata_uuid>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "(since: 5\\&.0)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"the main filesystem UUID is the metadata_uuid, which stores the new UUID "
"only in the superblock while all metadata blocks still have the UUID set at "
"mkfs time, see B<btrfstune>(8) for more"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<mixed_backref>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 2\\&.6\\&.31)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "the last major disk format change, improved backreferences, now default"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<mixed_groups>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 2\\&.6\\&.37)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"mixed data and metadata block groups, ie\\&. the data and metadata are not "
"separated and occupy the same block groups, this mode is suitable for small "
"volumes as there are no constraints how the remaining space should be used "
"(compared to the split mode, where empty metadata space cannot be used for "
"data and vice versa)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"on the other hand, the final layout is quite unpredictable and possibly "
"highly fragmented, which means worse performance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<no_holes>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.14)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"improved representation of file extents where holes are not explicitly "
"stored as an extent, saves a few percent of metadata if sparse files are used"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<raid1c34>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "(since: 5\\&.5)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "extended RAID1 mode with copies on 3 or 4 devices respectively"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<raid56>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.9)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "the filesystem contains or contained a raid56 profile of block groups"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<rmdir_subvol>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 4\\&.18)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"indicate that B<rmdir>(2) syscall can delete an empty subvolume just like an "
"ordinary directory\\&. Note that this feature only depends on the kernel "
"version\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "B<skinny_metadata>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid "(since: 3\\&.10)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye opensuse-leap-15-3
msgid ""
"reduced-size metadata for extent references, saves a few percent of metadata"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<supported_checksums>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"list of checksum algorithms supported by the kernel module, the respective "
"modules or built-in implementing the algorithms need to be present to mount "
"the filesystem"
msgstr ""

#. type: SS
#: debian-bullseye
#, no-wrap
msgid "SWAPFILE SUPPORT"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"The swapfile is supported since kernel 5\\&.0\\&. Use B<swapon>(8) to "
"activate the swapfile\\&. There are some limitations of the implementation "
"in btrfs and linux swap subsystem:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "filesystem - must be only single device"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "filesystem - must have only I<single> data profile"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "swapfile - the containing subvolume cannot be snapshotted"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "swapfile - must be preallocated"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "swapfile - must be nodatacow (ie\\&. also nodatasum)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "swapfile - must not be compressed"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"The limitations come namely from the COW-based design and mapping layer of "
"blocks that allows the advanced features like relocation and multi-device "
"filesystems\\&. However, the swap subsystem expects simpler mapping and no "
"background changes of the file blocks once they\\(cqve been attached to swap"
"\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"With active swapfiles, the following whole-filesystem operations will skip "
"swapfile extents or may fail:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"balance - block groups with swapfile extents are skipped and reported, the "
"rest will be processed normally"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "resize grow - unaffected"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"resize shrink - works as long as the extents are outside of the shrunk range"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"device add - a new device does not interfere with existing swapfile and this "
"operation will work, though no new swapfile can be activated afterwards"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"device delete - if the device has been added as above, it can be also deleted"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "device replace - ditto"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"When there are no active swapfiles and a whole-filesystem exclusive "
"operation is running (ie\\&. balance, device delete, shrink), the swapfiles "
"cannot be temporarily activated\\&. The operation must finish first\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# truncate -s 0 swapfile\n"
"# chattr +C swapfile\n"
"# fallocate -l 2G swapfile\n"
"# chmod 0600 swapfile\n"
"# mkswap swapfile\n"
"# swapon swapfile\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: SH
#: debian-bullseye
#, no-wrap
msgid "CHECKSUM ALGORITHMS"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"There are several checksum algorithms supported\\&. The default and backward "
"compatible is I<crc32c>\\&. Since kernel 5\\&.5 there are three more with "
"different characteristics and trade-offs regarding speed and strength\\&. "
"The following list may help you to decide which one to select\\&."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<CRC32C> (32bit digest)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid ""
"default, best backward compatibility, very fast, modern CPUs have "
"instruction-level support, not collision-resistant but still good error "
"detection capabilities"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
msgid "B<XXHASH> (64bit digest)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: debian-bullseye
